value.title: Video of Capitol riot shown at Trump impeachment trial 'literally took my breath away': Meghan McCain
value.excerpt: Conservative "The View" co-host Meghan McCain said Wednesday that video of last month's Capitol riot that was played at former President Donald Trump's impeachment trial "literally took my breath away".

value.title: Del. Plaskett says Jan. 6 rally didn't have permit to march to the Capitol until Trump stepped in
value.excerpt: Del. Stacey Plaskett, D-Virgin Islands, claimed Wednesday that the “Save America” rally did not have a permit to march to the Capitol on Jan. 6 until President Trump stepped in.

value.title: Meadows accuses House impeachment managers of 'conveniently leaving out' one line from Trump's Jan. 6 speech
value.excerpt: President Trump’s former chief of staff Mark Meadows accused House impeachment managers of “conveniently” leaving out a line from Trump’s pre-Capitol riot speech, where he told supporters to “peacefully and patriotically” make their voices heard.

value.title: Chip Roy slams Biden's 'purposeful' and 'deplorable' refusal to enforce immigration laws
value.excerpt: Rep. Chip Roy, R-Texas, slammed President Biden on Monday for what he described as a "purposeful" and "deplorable" refusal to enforce U.S. immigration laws.

value.title: Psaki says Biden 'respects this kind of protest' as Mark Cuban stops playing anthem at Mavericks games
value.excerpt: White House press secretary Jen Psaki said she hadn’t spoken to President Biden about Mark Cuban’s decision to stop playing the national anthem before Mavericks’ games, but believes he respects this kind of peaceful protest at sporting events.

value.title: Democrats dub Trump the 'inciter-in-chief' for provoking mob, refusing to stop Jan. 6 attack

value.title: Fulton County prosecutors launch criminal investigation into Trump phone call with Georgia secretary of state
value.excerpt: Georgia prosecutors opened a criminal investigation into former President Trump's efforts to overturn the 2020 presidential election in the state, including his phone call with Georgia Secretary of State Brad Raffensperger in which Trump suggested the Republicans "find" enough votes to change the results.

value.title: Biden actions against oil and gas industry producing 'chilling effect' against energy workers: George P. Bush
value.excerpt: Texas Land Commissioner George P. Bush said Wednesday that President Biden's immediate moves against the oil and gas industry produced a "chilling effect" against energy workers around the country.

value.title: Dozens of celebrities call on Joe Biden, Kamala Harris to shut down the Dakota Access Pipeline
value.excerpt: Dozens of celebrities signed a letter to President Joe Biden and Vice President Kamala Harris calling on their administration to shut down the Dakota Access Pipeline for good.

value.title: Laid-off Keystone pipeline workers slam job-killing Biden decision: Future 'completely taken away'
value.excerpt: Laid-off Keystone XL pipeline workers in Fouke, Ark., blasted President Biden's order canceling the project.

value.title: Tom Homan: 'Biden has declared the entire country a sanctuary jurisdiction'
value.excerpt: Former Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) Acting Director Tom Homan argued on Wednesday that “President Biden has declared the entire country a sanctuary jurisdiction,” which he said means “more tragedies are going to come.”

value.title: Wisconsin Dem governor 'not sure' he'll attend Biden event next week: report
value.excerpt: President Biden will travel to Wisconsin next week for his first "business" trip since taking office in January -- but the state's Democratic governor says he's "not sure" he'll be on hand to greet the president.

value.title: Trump ‘beyond angry’ with impeachment defense team’s showing: sources
value.excerpt: Former President Trump was “furious” and “beyond angry” over his defense team’s showing on Day One of his second impeachment trial, two sources told Fox News late Tuesday.

value.title: FLASHBACK: Obama Defense Sec. says Biden as VP was wrong on nearly every big foreign policy issue
value.excerpt: President Biden is expected to make his first visit to the Pentagon as Commander-in-Chief on Wednesday alongside Vice President Kamala Harris.

value.title: Why Trump lawyer David Schoen covered his head with every sip of water
value.excerpt: David Schoen unwittingly gave Twitter a lesson in orthodox Jewish customs during former President Donald Trump’s impeachment trial on Tuesday.

value.title: Biden OMB pick Tanden called out during confirmation hearing for anti-GOP tweets, says 'I'm sorry'
value.excerpt: Minutes into her confirmation hearing, President Biden's nominee for director of the White House Office of Management and Budget Neera Tanden had to address concerns over hostile tweets she has posted against various Republican lawmakers.

value.title: Gingrich: Senators who vote to convict Trump take part in 'profound attack on the American system'
value.excerpt: Lawmakers who vote to convict former President Donald Trump of incitement of insurrection and bar him from holding office again would be engaged in a "profound attack on the American system," former House Speaker Newt Gingrich told "Hannity" Monday night.

value.title: Texas sheriff claims Biden 'defunding ICE by memo': 'We have a full nullification of the law going on here'
value.excerpt: Reports that illegal aliens are being released from custody into the United States without being tested for COVID-19 are "absolutely true," Jackson County, Texas Sheriff A.J. Louderback told "Tucker Carlson Tonight" Monday.

value.title: Paul Manafort can't be tried in NY after Trump's pardon says state court
value.excerpt: Paul Manafort cannot be prosecuted in New York, highest court rules  The New York Court of Appeals has rejected the Manhattan DA's bid to review the lower courts’ rulings on denying Paul Manafort's prosecution.

value.title: Liz Cheney in Donald Trump Jr.’s 2022 crosshairs
value.excerpt: It’s a long way down the road, but it appears Donald Trump Jr.’s already making plans to travel to Wyoming next year to target Rep. Liz Cheney in the Republican primaries as she runs for re-election.

value.title: Sen. Tim Scott: Trump is 'simply not guilty' on impeachment
value.excerpt: Former President Donald Trump is "simply not guilty" of inciting an insurrection against the United States government, Sen. Tim Scott R-S.C., told "America Reports" on Monday.

value.title: Nikki Haley calls Biden's executive order about transgender athletics an 'attack on women's rights'
value.excerpt: Nikki Haley has joined voices in opposition of President Biden’s executive order calling on schools to allow transgender athletes to participate in the sport of their gender identity, arguing in a column published Monday that it’s an “attack on women’s rights.”

value.title: Donald Trump Jr. slams Super Bowl 2021 commercials as 'woketopia'
value.excerpt: Donald Trump Jr. wasn’t impressed with the Super Bowl 2021 commercial lineup. The son of former president Donald Trump tuned into the big game between the Tampa Bay Buccaneers and the Kansas City Chiefs on Sunday but was rolling his eyes at the broadcast almost immediately at the typically sought after ad breaks.

value.title: Biden sidesteps Trump impeachment trial questions: 'Let the Senate work that out’
value.excerpt: President Biden sidestepped questions about former President Donald Trump's impeachment trial, which is set to begin Tuesday, saying it is up to the Senate to "work that out."

value.title: Trump WH sign-language interpreter says Biden administration 'canceled and humiliated' her
value.excerpt: The White House sign-language interpreter who was outed as a supporter of former President Donald Trump said Sunday that she hasn’t been offered a return engagement since — and blasted critics who attacked her credibility and professionalism.

value.title: Trump will 'have a place in history' for Capitol riot but remains 'most popular figure' in GOP: Graham
value.excerpt: Former President Donald Trump will "have a place in history" for his role leading up to the riot at the U.S. Capitol last month, but he stills remains the "most popular figure" in the Republican Party, Sen. Lindsey Graham said Sunday.
